This place is not as famous as it's well known neighbor, you know the one, under the Brooklyn Bridge. But unlike their famous competition, you can get slices here. The slices are not thin and are not thick, they just right. The slice is crispy for most of the bites but subsides to chewiness towards the perfect golden crust, agian just right. The ratio of sauce and cheese is spot on, bubbling with nice amount browned and gooey spots of mozzarella. I love their simple menu, $3 cheese slices with $0.75 per topping. I like the pepperoni, they use the small thick kind here, the ones that turn in to tasty little cups. And all the slices come from a fresh pie. No glass case here filled with unending old pies. Cheese slices are ready to go, never more than a cheese pie or two behind the counter for freshness. Only need to heat slice to warm a custom topping. You can get a whole fresh pie as well, which I suggest for groups. I've never seen it too crowded here. But sorry locals this place is great and deserves more business.

Fascati's is my neighborhood slice joint and I wish I was in a position to offer a more favorable review but it seems like they've shifted focus onto saving costs (which kills the quality)  Pros: Service is quick (its a slice joint), decor is very clean, and the staff is friendly.  Cons: Their pizzas don't cut it. Between the hard crust (unproofed dough), the bland cheese and sauce, and the cardinal sin of adding the pepperonis when reheating the slice (instead of when they cook the pie - to save money)  Pizza Score (8/20pts - POOR) Crust 1/5 - Too Dense and flavorless - tasted un-proofed. Cheese 2/5 - Nothing special. Just inexpensive mozz. Sauce 2/5 - Just very neutral -  again, they're using cheap tomatoes without much spice or salt. Ratio 3/5 - The 3 ingredients were balanced - but the ingredients lacked.
